{"title_page": "Anders Mickelson", "text_new": "'''Anders Mickelson''', Finnish goldsmith, [[Faberg\u00e9 workmaster]]. Born 8 January in 1839 in Pyht\u00e4\u00e4, Finland<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digi.narc.fi/digi/view.ka?kuid=4568578|title=Christening register of Pyht\u00e4\u00e4 parish 1823-1850|last=|first=|date=|website=digi.narc.fi|language=sv|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. \n\nWorked in [[St. Petersburg]] as a apprentice from 1855<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digi.narc.fi/digi/view.ka?kuid=4803686|title=Pre-confirmation records of Pyht\u00e4\u00e4 parish 1854-1871|last=|first=|date=|website=digi.narc.fi|language=sv|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>, as a journeyman from 1859 and from 1867 ran his own workshop as a master. He was an [[outworker]] of [[Faberg\u00e9]], made mostly gold [[cigarette case]]s and small [[enamelling|enamelled]] objects. His initials are ''AM'' on the objects. Together with his fellow Faberg\u00e9 master Vassily Feodorovich Soloviev, he bought in 1912 or earlier, the workshop of master goldsmith Friedrich Theodor Ringe at 12 Malaja Morskaya from his widow Anna Karlovna Ringe.\n\nAnders Mickelson died in St. Petersburg 8 November in 1913<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digi.narc.fi/digi/view.ka?kuid=8137205|title=Deaths and burials of Evangelical Lutheran parish of Saint Mary 1904-1914|last=|first=|date=|website=digi.narc.fi|language=ru|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n\n* H.C. Bainbridge, ''Peter Carl Faberg\u00e9: Goldsmith and Jeweller to the Russian Imperial Court'' (1966)\n* G.von Habsburg-Lothringen & A.von Solodkoff, ''Faberg\u00e9 - Court Jeweler to the Tsars'' (1979) {{ISBN|0-914427-09-1}}\n* Ulla Tillander-Godenhielm, ''Faberg\u00e9n suomalaiset mestarit'' (Faberg\u00e9\u00b4s Finnish masters) (2011) p. 191. {{ISBN|978-951-31-5878-1}}  \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mickelson, Anders}}\n[[Category:Finnish goldsmiths]]\n[[Category:Faberg\u00e9 workmasters]]\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "'''Anders Mickelson''', Finnish goldsmith, [[Faberg\u00e9 workmaster]]. Born 8 January in 1839 in Pyht\u00e4\u00e4, Finland<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digi.narc.fi/digi/view.ka?kuid=4568578|title=Christening register of Pyht\u00e4\u00e4 parish 1823-1850|last=|first=|date=|website=digi.narc.fi|language=sv|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>. \n\nWorked in [[St. Petersburg]] as a apprentice from 1855<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digi.narc.fi/digi/view.ka?kuid=4803686|title=Pre-confirmation records of Pyht\u00e4\u00e4 parish 1854-1871|last=|first=|date=|website=digi.narc.fi|language=sv|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>, as a journeyman from 1859 and from 1867 ran his own workshop as a master. He was an [[outworker]] of [[Faberg\u00e9]], made mostly gold [[cigarette case]]s and small [[enamelling|enamelled]] objects. His initials are ''AM'' on the objects. Together with his fellow Faberg\u00e9 master Vassily Feodorovich Soloviev, he bought in 1912 or earlier, the workshop of master goldsmith Friedrich Theodor Ringe at 12 Malaja Morskaya from his widow Anna Karlovna Ringe.\n\nAnders Mickelson died in St. Petersburg 8 November in 1913.\n\n==References==\n\n* H.C. Bainbridge, ''Peter Carl Faberg\u00e9: Goldsmith and Jeweller to the Russian Imperial Court'' (1966)\n* G.von Habsburg-Lothringen & A.von Solodkoff, ''Faberg\u00e9 - Court Jeweler to the Tsars'' (1979) {{ISBN|0-914427-09-1}}\n* Ulla Tillander-Godenhielm, ''Faberg\u00e9n suomalaiset mestarit'' (Faberg\u00e9\u00b4s Finnish masters) (2011) p. 191. {{ISBN|978-951-31-5878-1}}  \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mickelson, Anders}}\n[[Category:Finnish goldsmiths]]\n[[Category:Faberg\u00e9 workmasters]]\n[[Category:1839 births]]\n[[Category:1913 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "KjoWi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Link to death and burial records.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anders_Mickelson"}
{"title_page": "Karen (slang)", "text_new": "[[File:Kate_Gosselin.jpg|thumb|American television personality [[Kate Gosselin]] in 2008; Gosselin is often used in ''Karen'' memes.]]\n\n'''''Karen''''' is a [[slang]] term that is aimed towards white women; in particular, the term most often refers to middle-class white women with disproportionate senses of entitlement. One of the most common ''Karen'' stereotypes is that of a middle-aged [[soccer mom]] with a poor attitude towards customer service workers; such women are often depicted as demanding to \"speak to the manager\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/5/21079162/karen-name-insult-meme-manager|title=Karen: The anti-vaxxer soccer mom with speak-to-the-manager hair, explained|last=Romano|first=Aja|date=2020-02-05|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nThe origins of ''Karen'' as an internet meme predominately date back to an anonymous [[Reddit]] user, Fuck_You_Karen, who would make posts ranting about and denigrating his ex-wife Karen, who he alleged had \"taken\" both his children and, later, his house during divorce proceedings. The unintentional entertainment value provided by the posts led to the creation of a subreddit in 2017, r/FuckYouKaren, to both compile a narrative and share memes about the posts. Since Fuck_You_Karen delete his account, the subreddit has since refocused to memes about the stereotype in general rather than one specific woman.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe [[Karen (name)|name ''Karen'']] has several negative connotations that predate the internet meme; the most notable uses of ''Karen'' as a name in popular culture include [[Lorraine Bracco]]'s depiction of [[Karen Friedman Hill]] in the 1990 film ''[[Goodfellas]]'' and [[Amanda Seyfried]]'s ditzy schoolgirl character in the 2003 film ''[[Mean Girls]]''. Other uses of ''Karen'' as the punchline of a joke include [[Dane Cook]]'s 2005 sketch about \"the friend nobody likes\", and a 2016 internet meme regarding an (officially unnamed) woman in an advert for the [[Nintendo Switch]] console who exhibits antisocial behaviour.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Usage and examples ==\nThe ''Karen'' archetype carries several stereotypes that are common to \"[[Basic (slang)|basic]] white women\"; most notable is the stereotype that a ''Karen'' will demand to \"speak with the manager\" of a metaphorical service provider. Further common stereotypes associated with the ''Karen'' pejorative include [[anti-vaccination]] beliefs and a [[Bob cut|bob haircut]] with blonde [[Hair highlighting|highlights]]\u2014pictures of [[Kate Gosselin]] during the airing of ''[[Kate Plus 8]]'' were used in earlier memes about a \"can-I-speak-to-your-manager haircut\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/human-interest/2018/08/bbq-becky-permit-patty-apple-store-lady-why-laughing-at-white-entitlement-feels-so-appropriate.html|title=Why Memes Making Fun of White People Demanding to \u201cSpeak to the Manager!\u201d Are So Popular Right Now|last=Dozier|first=Rob|date=2018-08-21|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>, and continue to be used in ''Karen'' memes<ref name=\":0\" />\u2014, engagement in [[multi-level marketing]] schemes, and Facebook posts sharing trite motivational messages.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe stereotype saw greater prominence in mid-2019, when the formation of [[Tropical Storm Karen (2019)|Tropical Storm Karen]] in the [[Atlantic hurricane|Atlantic hurricane basin]] led to memes likening the storm to the stereotype; several users made jokes about the storm wanting to \"speak with the manager\", with images photoshopped to include the \"Karen haircut\" on either the hurricane or its forecasted path.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5683398/tropical-storm-karen-memes/|title=Tropical Storm Karen Has the Internet Saying the Storm 'Wants to Speak to a Manager'|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> At the same time, the term gained prominence in Hispanic and African-American communities as a way to describe racist suburban white women who would call the police on people of colour for minor trespasses such as holding [[Barbecue|barbecues]] or children operating [[Lemonade stand|lemonade stands]]. This usage of the term saw use in early 2020 to describe similar women who would passively-aggressively enforce [[quarantine]] during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailywire.com/news/feminists-worry-that-internet-karen-meme-is-mired-in-sexism|title=Feminists Worry That Internet \u2018Karen\u2019 Meme Is \u2018Mired In Sexism\u2019|website=The Daily Wire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nThe term also saw heightened scrutiny in April 2020, with considerable debate over whether the term constitutes a slur; a Twitter account named \"Friends of Journalism\" asserted the term to be \"an equivalent of the [[n-word]] for white women\" and polled Twitter users on whether they would like to see it banned; 96% of respondents answered in the negative. At the same time, journalist and radical feminist [[Julie Bindel]] asked on her Twitter feed, \"Does anyone else think the \u2018Karen\u2019 slur is woman-hating and based on [[Class discrimination|class prejudice]]?\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/04/06/karen-slur-meme-coronavirus-pandemic-julie-bindel-twitter-feminism-white-privilege-class/|title=In these trying times, lesbian radical feminist Julie Bindel is debating whether \u2018Karen\u2019 is a slur. Yes, really|last=|first=|date=2020-04-06|website=[[PinkNews]]|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Bindel's comments provoked a wide-ranging debate; ''[[The Guardian]]'' journalist [[Hadley Freeman]] replied to Bindel saying that it was \"sexist, ageist, and classist, in that order\". Freeman's own comments received criticism from people of colour \u2014 who believed Bindel and Freeman were denigrating their use of the term to discuss racism \u2014 and several misogynist troll comments.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Freeman|first=Hadley|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2020/apr/13/the-karen-meme-is-everywhere-and-it-has-become-mired-in-sexism|title=The 'Karen' meme is everywhere \u2013 and it has become mired in sexism|date=2020-04-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-21|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Other critics of Bindel's statements asserted that \"claiming Karen is a slur is a very Karen thing to do\" and likened it to Bindel's opposition to the term ''[[TERF]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bitchmedia.org/article/very-online/the-karen-meme-isnt-a-slur-its-a-social-critique|title=\u201cKaren\u201d Isn\u2019t a Slur\u2014It\u2019s A Critique of Entitled White Womanhood|website=Bitch Media|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/04/06/karen-slur-meme-coronavirus-pandemic-julie-bindel-twitter-feminism-white-privilege-class/|title=In these trying times, lesbian radical feminist Julie Bindel is debating whether \u2018Karen\u2019 is a slur. Yes, really|date=2020-04-06|website=PinkNews - Gay news, reviews and comment from the world's most read lesbian, gay, bisexual, and trans news service|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Becky (slang)|''Becky'' (slang)]]\n* [[Gammon (insult)|''Gammon'' (insult)]]\n* [[OK Boomer]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Pejorative terms for women]]\n[[Category:Anti-European and anti-white slurs]]\n[[Category:Stereotypes of white Americans]]\n[[Category:Stereotypes of middle class women]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2017]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Kate_Gosselin.jpg|thumb|American television personality [[Kate Gosselin]] in 2008; Gosselin is often used in ''Karen'' memes.]]\n\n'''''Karen''''' is a [[slang]] term that is aimed towards white women; in particular, the term most often refers to middle-class white women with disproportionate senses of entitlement. One of the most common ''Karen'' stereotypes is that of a middle-aged [[soccer mom]] with a poor attitude towards customer service workers; such women are often depicted as demanding to \"speak to the manager\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/5/21079162/karen-name-insult-meme-manager|title=Karen: The anti-vaxxer soccer mom with speak-to-the-manager hair, explained|last=Romano|first=Aja|date=2020-02-05|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== Origins ==\nThe origins of ''Karen'' as an internet meme predominately date back to an anonymous [[Reddit]] user, Fuck_You_Karen, who would make posts ranting about and denigrating his ex-wife Karen, who he alleged had \"taken\" both his children and, later, his house during divorce proceedings. The unintentional entertainment value provided by the posts led to the creation of a subreddit in 2017, r/FuckYouKaren, to both compile a narrative and share memes about the posts. Since Fuck_You_Karen delete his account, the subreddit has since refocused to memes about the stereotype in general rather than one specific woman.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe [[Karen (name)|name ''Karen'']] has several negative connotations that predate the internet meme; the most notable uses of ''Karen'' as a name in popular culture include [[Lorraine Bracco]]'s depiction of [[Karen Friedman Hill]] in the 1990 film ''[[Goodfellas]]'' and[[Amanda Seyfried]]'s ditzy schoolgirl character in the 2003 film ''[[Mean Girls]]''. Other uses of ''Karen'' as the punchline of a joke include [[Dane Cook]]'s 2005 sketch about \"the friend nobody likes\", and a 2016 internet meme regarding an (officially unnamed) woman in an advert for the [[Nintendo Switch]] console who exhibits antisocial behaviour.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Usage and examples ==\nThe ''Karen'' archetype carries several stereotypes that are common to \"[[Basic (slang)|basic]] white women\"; most notable is the stereotype that a ''Karen'' will demand to \"speak with the manager\" of a metaphorical service provider. Further common stereotypes associated with the ''Karen'' pejorative include [[anti-vaccination]] beliefs and a [[Bob cut|bob haircut]] with blonde [[Hair highlighting|highlights]]\u2014pictures of [[Kate Gosselin]] during the airing of ''[[Kate Plus 8]]'' were used in earlier memes about a \"can-I-speak-to-your-manager haircut\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/human-interest/2018/08/bbq-becky-permit-patty-apple-store-lady-why-laughing-at-white-entitlement-feels-so-appropriate.html|title=Why Memes Making Fun of White People Demanding to \u201cSpeak to the Manager!\u201d Are So Popular Right Now|last=Dozier|first=Rob|date=2018-08-21|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>, and continue to be used in ''Karen'' memes<ref name=\":0\" />\u2014, engagement in [[multi-level marketing]] schemes, and Facebook posts sharing trite motivational messages.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe stereotype saw greater prominence in mid-2019, when the formation of [[Tropical Storm Karen (2019)|Tropical Storm Karen]] in the [[Atlantic hurricane|Atlantic hurricane basin]] led to memes likening the storm to the stereotype; several users made jokes about the storm wanting to \"speak with the manager\", with images photoshopped to include the \"Karen haircut\" on either the hurricane or its forecasted path.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5683398/tropical-storm-karen-memes/|title=Tropical Storm Karen Has the Internet Saying the Storm 'Wants to Speak to a Manager'|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> At the same time, the term gained prominence in Hispanic and African-American communities as a way to describe racist suburban white women who would call the police on people of colour for minor trespasses such as holding [[Barbecue|barbecues]] or children operating [[Lemonade stand|lemonade stands]]. This usage of the term saw use in early 2020 to describe similar women who would passively-aggressively enforce [[quarantine]] during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailywire.com/news/feminists-worry-that-internet-karen-meme-is-mired-in-sexism|title=Feminists Worry That Internet \u2018Karen\u2019 Meme Is \u2018Mired In Sexism\u2019|website=The Daily Wire|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nThe term also saw heightened scrutiny in April 2020, with considerable debate over whether the term constitutes a slur; a Twitter account named \"Friends of Journalism\" asserted the term to be \"an equivalent of the [[n-word]] for white women\" and polled Twitter users on whether they would like to see it banned; 96% of respondents answered in the negative. At the same time, journalist and radical feminist [[Julie Bindel]] asked on her Twitter feed, \"Does anyone else think the \u2018Karen\u2019 slur is woman-hating and based on [[Class discrimination|class prejudice]]?\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/04/06/karen-slur-meme-coronavirus-pandemic-julie-bindel-twitter-feminism-white-privilege-class/|title=In these trying times, lesbian radical feminist Julie Bindel is debating whether \u2018Karen\u2019 is a slur. Yes, really|last=|first=|date=2020-04-06|website=[[PinkNews]]|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Bindel's comments provoked a wide-ranging debate; ''[[The Guardian]]'' journalist [[Hadley Freeman]] replied to Bindel saying that it was \"sexist, ageist, and classist, in that order\". Freeman's own comments received criticism from people of colour \u2014 who believed Bindel and Freeman were denigrating their use of the term to discuss racism \u2014 and several misogynist troll comments.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Freeman|first=Hadley|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2020/apr/13/the-karen-meme-is-everywhere-and-it-has-become-mired-in-sexism|title=The 'Karen' meme is everywhere \u2013 and it has become mired in sexism|date=2020-04-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-21|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Other critics of Bindel's statements asserted that \"claiming Karen is a slur is a very Karen thing to do\" and likened it to Bindel's opposition to the term ''[[TERF]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bitchmedia.org/article/very-online/the-karen-meme-isnt-a-slur-its-a-social-critique|title=\u201cKaren\u201d Isn\u2019t a Slur\u2014It\u2019s A Critique of Entitled White Womanhood|website=Bitch Media|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/04/06/karen-slur-meme-coronavirus-pandemic-julie-bindel-twitter-feminism-white-privilege-class/|title=In these trying times, lesbian radical feminist Julie Bindel is debating whether \u2018Karen\u2019 is a slur. Yes, really|date=2020-04-06|website=PinkNews - Gay news, reviews and comment from the world's most read lesbian, gay, bisexual, and trans news service|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Becky (slang)|''Becky'' (slang)]]\n* [[Gammon (insult)|''Gammon'' (insult)]]\n* [[OK Boomer]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:Pejorative terms for women]]\n[[Category:Anti-European and anti-white slurs]]\n[[Category:Stereotypes of white Americans]]\n[[Category:Stereotypes of middle class women]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2017]]\n", "name_user": "Bender235", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOrigins", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karen_(slang)"}
{"title_page": "Mark Lee (singer)", "text_new": "{{unreliable sources|date=June 2019}}\n{{short description|Canadian-Korean rapper}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mark Lee \n| birth_name         = Mark Lee\n| native_name        = \uc774\ub9c8\ud06c\n| image              = 181012 Mark KBS '\ubba4\uc9c1\ubc45\ud06c' \ub9ac\ud5c8\uc124 \ucd9c\uadfc\uae38 \uc9c1\ucea0 \uc601\uc0c1.png\n| caption            = Mark Lee in October 2018\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1999|8|2}}\n| birth_place        = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| nationality        = Canadian\n| other_names        = Lee Min-hyung\n| education          = [[School of Performing Arts Seoul]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Rapper|singer|songwriter}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[K-pop]]|[[hip-hop]]}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals}}\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[SM Entertainment|SM]]|[[Avex Trax]]|[[Capitol Records|Capitol]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[NCT (band)|NCT]]|[[NCT 127]]|[[NCT U]]|[[NCT Dream]]|[[SuperM]]|[[SM Rookies]]|[[SM Town]]}}\n}}\n| module2            = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n| title           = [[Korean name]]\n| hangul          = \uc774\ubbfc\ud615\n| hanja           = {{linktext|\u674e|\u654f|\u4ea8}}\n| rr              = I Minhyeong\n| mr              = Yi Minhy\u014fng\n| hangulstage     = \ub9c8\ud06c\n| rrstage         = Ma Keu\n| mrstage         = Ma K'\u016d\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Mark Lee''' (born August 2, 1999), known professionally as '''Mark''', is a Canadian rapper and singer-songwriter based in South Korea. He is best known as a member of the South Korean boy group [[NCT (band)|NCT]] and its sub-units NCT U, [[NCT 127]], and [[NCT Dream]]. Mark is also best friends with fellow group member Haechan and childhood friend Grace. Mark made his debut in April 2016 as a member of rotational unit NCT U, became a member of Seoul-based fixed unit NCT 127 in July 2016 and also a member of NCT Dream in August 2016. In October 2019, Mark debuted as a member of the supergroup [[SuperM]].\n\n==Career==\n===2013\u20132015: SM Rookies===\nIn 2012, Mark joined [[SM Entertainment]] after passing the SM Global Audition in Canada in 2010.\n\nIn December 2013, Mark was introduced as a member of [[SM Rookies]], a pre-debut training team managed by SM Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mydaily.co.kr/new_yk/html/read.php?newsid=201312171039311138|title='SM\ub8e8\ud0a4\uc988' \ub9c8\ud06c\u00b7\uc9c0\uc131\u00b7\ud55c\uc194 \uc804\uaca9\uacf5\uac1c, \uc548\ubb34\uac00 \ud1a0\ub2c8\ud14c\uc2a4\ud0c0 \uadf9\ucc2c|last=Jeon|first=Won|date=December 13, 2013|publisher=MyDaily|accessdate=July 18, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Mark appeared on [[Exo 90:2014]], a reality TV Show starring [[Exo (band)|Exo]], alongside other members of the SM Rookies program, where they performed songs and recreated music videos of prominent 90s [[K-pop]] idols.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.osen.co.kr/article/G1109972619|title=[\uc5b4\uc800\uaed8TV] \u2018\uc5d1\uc18c902014\u2019 K\ud31d \uc2dc\ud5d8, 90 \ubc18\uac11\uace0 2014 \uc0c8\ub86d\uace0|last=Kim|first=Sara|date=October 4, 2014|publisher=Osen|accessdate=July 18, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Mark appeared on [[Disney Channel Korea]]'s ''[[The Mickey Mouse Club]]'' as a Mouseketeer alongside other members of the SM Rookies program, some of which are currently in [[NCT Dream]]. The show aired from July 23 to December 17, 2015 and was hosted by [[Leeteuk]] of [[Super Junior]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tvreport.co.kr/?c=news&m=newsview&idx=743716|title=\ub514\uc988\ub2c8\ucc44\ub110, \ud55c\uad6d\ud310 \u2018\ubbf8\ud0a4\ub9c8\uc6b0\uc2a4\ud074\ub7fd\u2019 \uc81c\uc791 \u2018SM \ub8e8\ud0a4\uc988 \ucd9c\uc5f0\u2019|last=Hwang|first=Geung-ji|date=July 9, 2015|publisher=TV Report|accessdate=July 18, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u2013present: NCT and solo endeavors===\nIn April 2016, SM Entertainment confirmed Mark alongside five other members of the SM Rookies program to debut as members of [[NCT (band)|NCT]] and its first subgroup, NCT U. On April 9, Mark, alongside [[Lee Tae-yong|Taeyong]], Doyoung, [[Ten (singer)|Ten]] and Jaehyun debuted with the digital single \"The 7th Sense\", which he and Taeyong participated in the writing of.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201604061758581112853_2|title=NCT U confirms lineup, set to unveil singles 'The 7th Sense,' 'Without You'|last=Son|first=Ji-hyoung|date=April 6, 2016|publisher=[[The Korea Herald]]|accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, SM confirmed Mark as a member of NCT's second subgroup, [[NCT 127]], alongside Taeyong, Taeil, Yuta, Jaehyun, Winwin and Haechan. NCT 127 made their official debut with ''[[NCT 127 (EP)|NCT #127]]'' and title track \"Fire Truck\" on July 10, 2016.<ref name=genre>{{cite web|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201607101242101223011_1|title=NCT 127 \uc804\uace1 \uc74c\uc6d0 \uacf5\uac1c, \ubcf4\ub108\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub799\uae4c\uc9c0 \ucd1d 7\uace1 \uc218\ub85d|date=July 10, 2016|website=Herald Corporation|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, SM confirmed Mark as a member of NCT's third subgroup, [[NCT Dream]], alongside Renjun, Jeno, Haechan, Jaemin, Chenle and Jisung. The group made their official debut on August 24, 2016, with the single \"Chewing Gum\".\n\nIn September 2016, Mark featured on [[Henry Lau]]'s \"Going Through Your Heart\", an original soundtrack for the [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]] drama, [[Sweet Stranger and Me]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/909461wpp/henry-ncts-mark-plus-kim-jong-kook-sing-ost-man-living-house|title= Henry And NCT\u2019s Mark Plus Kim Jong Kook To Sing OST For \"The Man Living In Our House\"|date=October 24, 2016|website=Soompi|language=en}}</ref> This marked his first solo endeavour since debuting under NCT. \n \nIn January 2017, Mark joined ''[[High School Rapper]]'', a survival hip hop reality TV show which aired on [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]].<ref name=\"crap-source1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/935159wpp/ncts-mark-audition-mnets-new-hip-hop-show-high-school-rapper|title= NCT\u2019s Mark To Audition For Mnet\u2019s New Hip Hop Show \"High School Rapper\"|date=January 9, 2017|website=Soompi|language=en}}</ref> He made it to the finals and performed an original song, \"Drop\" featuring labelmate, [[Kang Seul-gi|Seulgi]] of [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]. He subsequently placed 7th overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/967909wpp/watch-high-school-rapper-reveals-final-winner-performances-special-guests|title= Watch: \"High School Rapper\" Reveals Final Winner And Performances With Special Guests|date=April 1, 2017|website=Soompi|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Mark collaborated with Exo's [[Xiumin]] on single, [[Young & Free]]. The single was released through [[SM Station Season 2|Season 2]] of SM Entertainment's digital music project [[SM Station]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/music/now/read?oid=311&aid=0000749346|title=\uc5d1\uc18c \uc2dc\uc6b0\ubbfc\u00b7NCT \ub9c8\ud06c, 'SM\uc2a4\ud14c\uc774\uc158'\uc73c\ub85c \uc2a4\ud398\uc15c \ub4c0\uc624 \uacb0\uc131|access-date=2017-06-29|language=ko}}</ref> In the same month, Mark appeared in the first season of the music variety show ''Snowball Project''. He teamed up with [[Park Jae-jung (singer)|Park Jae-jung]] and released \"Lemonade Love\" on July 21, also through SM Station, which was produced by former labelmate Henry Lau and [[Yoon Jong-shin]].<ref name=\"snowballproject\">{{cite web |title=\"\ub208\ub369\uc774 \ucd9c\uaca9\"...\ubc15\uc7ac\uc815X\ub9c8\ud06c, \u2018\ub808\ubaa8\ub124\uc774\ub4dc \ub7ec\ube0c\u2019 \uc624\ub298(21\uc77c) \ubc1c\ud45c |url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/014/0003847621 |website=n.news.naver.com |accessdate=June 30, 2019 |language=ko |date=July 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/2017/05/23/sm-mystic-entertainment-team-new-music-variety-show/|title=Parc Jae Jung And NCT's Mark Are The First Team-Up For SM And Mystic Entertainment's New Variety Show {{!}} Soompi|website=www.soompi.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Mark was named as one of the main emcees of the music program ''[[Show! Music Core]]''. He subsequently left the program in January 2019 to focus on activities with NCT 127.<ref name=\"showmucic\">{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=213&aid=0001014733|title=\uc639\uc131\uc6b0\u00b7\ubbf8\ub098\u00b7\ub9c8\ud06c, '\uc74c\uc545\uc911\uc2ec' \u65b0 MC \ubc1c\ud0c1 [\uacf5\uc2dd]|date=January 26, 2018|website=Herald Corporation|language=ko}}</ref>\nIn May 2018, he became a regular cast member on the [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]] reality TV show ''[[It's Dangerous Beyond The Blankets]]''.<ref name=\"blankets\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=201805031602080410|title=MBC \uce21 \"NCT \ub9c8\ud06c \u2018\uc774\ubd88\ubc16\uc740 \uc704\ud5d8\ud574\u2019 \ucd9c\uc5f0 \ub17c\uc758\uc911\"|date=May 3, 2018}}</ref> In October 2018, Mark released the song \"Dream Me\" with Red Velvet's [[Joy (singer)|Joy]] for the soundtrack of the KBS drama ''[[The Ghost Detective]].''\n\nOn December 31, 2018, Mark became the first member to officially graduate from NCT Dream.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=109&aid=0003850884|title=\"[\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5] NCT \ub9c8\ud06c, \uc62c\ud574 \ub9c8\uc9c0\ub9c9\uc73c\ub85c NCT DREAM \uc878\uc5c5\u2026\uc878\uc5c5\uc1a1 \uc218\ub85d\"|date=August 26, 2018|accessdate=July 1, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nOn August 7, 2019, Mark was confirmed as a member of [[SuperM]], a \"K-pop supergroup\" created by SM Entertainment in collaboration with [[Capitol Records]]. The group's promotions began in October and were  focused at the American market.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Jeff Benjamin |title=Super M, 'The Avengers Of K-Pop,' Unveiled By SM Entertainment And Capitol Music Group |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffbenjamin/2019/08/07/super-m-the-avengers-of-k-pop-unveiled-by-sm-entertainment-and-capitol-music-group/#355dfa061381 |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=Forbes |date=7 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=SM Entertainment and Capitol Records Team Up to Launch Super M |url=https://www.billboard.com/video/bbnews080819tiffanykpop2-8526949 |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=Billboard |date=8 August 2019}}</ref> SuperM's [[SuperM (EP)|self-titled debut EP]] was released on October 4, 2019 with lead single \"Jopping\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8532879/superm-the-1st-mini-album-billboard-200-no-1|title=SuperM Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart With 'The 1st Mini Album'|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, it was announced by SM Entertainment that Mark would return to and take part in NCT Dream future activities, as the sub-unit was to be re-branded and shifted away from its previous age-based graduation system.<ref>https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9357513/nct-dream-new-album-reload-return-of-mark</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|NCT discography|SuperM#Discography}}\n\n===Songs===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\" | Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! colspan=\"2\" | Peak chart<br />positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Sales\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Album\n|-\n!  style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%\" |[[Gaon Music Chart|KOR<br />Gaon]]<br /><ref name=\"Gaon\">{{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/|title=Gaon Chart|website=[[Gaon Chart]]|language=ko}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%\" |[[Billboard charts|US<br />World]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/charts/world-digital-songs|title=World Digital Songs|work=[[Billboard charts|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" | As lead artist\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Drop\" <small>(\ub450\uace0\uac00)</small><br />{{small|(featuring [[Kang Seul-gi|Seulgi]])}}\n|2017\n| 93 || \u2014\n|KOR: 46,443<ref>Cumulative sales for \"Drop\":\n* {{cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=S1020&targetTime=13&hitYear=2017&termGbn=week|title=Gaon Download Chart, Week 13|last=|first=|date=|website=Gaon Music Chart|publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=April 6, 2017}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=S1020&targetTime=14&hitYear=2017&termGbn=week|title=Gaon Download Chart, Week 14|last=|first=|date=|website=Gaon Music Chart|publisher=Korea Music Content Industry Association|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=April 13, 2017}}</ref>\n|''[[High School Rapper (season 1)#Final 2|School Rapper FINAL]]''\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" |Collaborations\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"[[Young & Free]]\"<br />{{small|(with [[Xiumin]])}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2017\n| 31 || 6\n|\n* KOR: 72,133<ref>Cumulative sales for \"Young & Free\":\n*{{Cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=S1020&targetTime=27&hitYear=2017&termGbn=week|title= 2017 Gaon Download Chart \u2013 Week 27|accessdate=2017-07-31}}\n*{{Cite web|url=http://gaonchart.co.kr/main/section/chart/online.gaon?nationGbn=T&serviceGbn=S1020&targetTime=28&hitYear=2017&termGbn=week|title= 2017 Gaon Download Chart \u2013 Week 28|accessdate=2017-07-31}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[SM Station Season 2]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Lemonade Love\"<br />{{small|(with [[Park Jae-jung (singer)|Park Jae-jung]])}}\n| 197 || 17\n|\n|-\n! colspan=\"6\" |Soundtrack appearances\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Going Through Your Heart\"<br />{{small|(with [[Henry Lau|Henry]])}}\n|2016\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|''[[Sweet Stranger and Me| Sweet Stranger and Me OST]]''\n|-\n!scope=row|\"Dream Me\" <small>(\ub098\ub77c\ub294 \uafc8)</small><br /><small>(with [[Joy (singer)|Joy]])</small>\n|2018\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|\n|''[[The Ghost Detective#Original soundtrack|The Ghost Detective OST]]''\n|-\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|NCT videography}}\n\n=== Television shows ===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Network\n! Role\n! Notes\n! Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2017\n| ''[[High School Rapper]]''\n| [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]\n| rowspan=\"1\" |Contestant\n|\n| <ref name=\"crap-source1\"/>\n|-\n| ''Snowball Project''\n| Naver TV\n| rowspan=\"1\" |Cast member\n|\n| <ref name=\"snowballproject\"/>\n|-\n| 2018\u20132019\n|''[[Show! Music Core]]''\n| [[MBC TV|MBC]]\n| Co-host\n|with [[Ong Seong-wu]] and [[Kang Mi-na]]\n| <ref name=\"showmucic\"/>\n|- \n| 2018\n| ''[[It's Dangerous Beyond The Blankets]]''\n| [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]\n| Main cast\n| Ep. 8\u201310 (Season 2)\n| <ref name=\"blankets\"/>\n|}\n\n=== Music videos ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Title\n! Year\n|-\n! scope=row | \"Young & Free\" {{small|(with [[Xiumin]])}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2017\n|-\n! scope=row | \"Lemonade Love\" {{small|(with [[Park Jae-jung (singer)|Park Jae-jung]])}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{see also|List of awards and nominations received by NCT}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[2018 MBC Entertainment Awards|18th MBC Entertainment Awards]]\n| Rookie Award in Music / Talk Show \u2013 Male\n| ''[[Show! Music Core]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{NCT (band)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Mark}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:NCT (band)]]\n[[Category:SuperM members]]\n[[Category:Canadian male rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian rappers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male dancers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian pop singers]]\n[[Category:Canadian musicians of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:School of Performing Arts Seoul alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriates in South Korea]]\n[[Category:K-pop singers]]\n[[Category:SM Entertainment artists]]\n[[Category:Korean-language singers of Canada]]\n[[Category:South Korean television personalities]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreliable sources|date=June 2019}}\n{{short description|Canadian-Korean rapper}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mark Lee \n| birth_name         = Mark Lee\n| native_name        = \uc774\ub9c8\ud06c\n| image              = 181012 Mark KBS '\ubba4\uc9c1\ubc45\ud06c' \ub9ac\ud5c8\uc124 \ucd9c\uadfc\uae38 \uc9c1\ucea0 \uc601\uc0c1.png\n| caption            = Mark Lee in October 2018\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1999|8|2}}\n| birth_place        = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| nationality        = Canadian\n| other_names        = Lee Min-hyung\n| education          = [[School of Performing Arts Seoul]]\n| occupation         = {{hlist|Rapper|singer|songwriter}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background       = solo_singer\n| genre            = {{hlist|[[K-pop]]|[[hip-hop]]}}\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals}}\n| years_active     = 2013\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[SM Entertainment|SM]]|[[Avex Trax]]|[[Capitol Records|Capitol]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[NCT (band)|NCT]]|[[NCT 127]]|[[NCT U]]|[[NCT Dream]]|[[SuperM]]|[[SM Rookies]]|[[SM Town]]}}\n}}\n| module2            = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n| title           = [[Korean name]]\n| hangul          = \uc774\ubbfc\ud615\n| hanja           = {{linktext|\u674e|\u654f|\u4ea8}}\n| rr              = I Minhyeong\n| mr              = Yi Minhy\u014fng\n| hangulstage     = \ub9c8\ud06c\n| rrstage         = Ma Keu\n| mrstage         = Ma K'\u016d\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Mark Lee''' (born August 2, 1999), known professionally as '''Mark''', is a Canadian rapper and singer-songwriter based in South Korea. He is best known as a member of the South Korean boy group [[NCT (band)|NCT]] and its sub-units NCT U, [[NCT 127]], and [[NCT Dream]]. Mark is also best friends with fellow group member Haechan, and Grace. Mark made his debut in April 2016 as a member of rotational unit NCT U, became a member of Seoul-based fixed unit NCT 127 in July 2016 and also a member of NCT Dream in August 2016. In October 2019, Mark debuted as a member of the supergroup [[SuperM]].\n\n==Career==\n===2013\u20132015: SM Rookies===\nIn 2012, Mark joined [[SM Entertainment]] after passing the SM Global Audition in Canada in 2010.\n\nIn December 2013, Mark was introduced as a member of [[SM Rookies]], a pre-debut training team managed by SM Entertainment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mydaily.co.kr/new_yk/html/read.php?newsid=201312171039311138|title='SM\ub8e8\ud0a4\uc988' \ub9c8\ud06c\u00b7\uc9c0\uc131\u00b7\ud55c\uc194 \uc804\uaca9\uacf5\uac1c, \uc548\ubb34\uac00 \ud1a0\ub2c8\ud14c\uc2a4\ud0c0 \uadf9\ucc2c|last=Jeon|first=Won|date=December 13, 2013|publisher=MyDaily|accessdate=July 18, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Mark appeared on [[Exo 90:2014]], a reality TV Show starring [[Exo (band)|Exo]], alongside other members of the SM Rookies program, where they performed songs and recreated music videos of prominent 90s [[K-pop]] idols.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.osen.co.kr/article/G1109972619|title=[\uc5b4\uc800\uaed8TV] \u2018\uc5d1\uc18c902014\u2019 K\ud31d \uc2dc\ud5d8, 90 \ubc18\uac11\uace0 2014 \uc0c8\ub86d\uace0|last=Kim|first=Sara|date=October 4, 2014|publisher=Osen|accessdate=July 18, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Mark appeared on [[Disney Channel Korea]]'s ''[[The Mickey Mouse Club]]'' as a Mouseketeer alongside other members of the SM Rookies program, some of which are currently in [[NCT Dream]]. The show aired from July 23 to December 17, 2015 and was hosted by [[Leeteuk]] of [[Super Junior]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tvreport.co.kr/?c=news&m=newsview&idx=743716|title=\ub514\uc988\ub2c8\ucc44\ub110, \ud55c\uad6d\ud310 \u2018\ubbf8\ud0a4\ub9c8\uc6b0\uc2a4\ud074\ub7fd\u2019 \uc81c\uc791 \u2018SM \ub8e8\ud0a4\uc988 \ucd9c\uc5f0\u2019|last=Hwang|first=Geung-ji|date=July 9, 2015|publisher=TV Report|accessdate=July 18, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n===2016\u2013present: NCT and solo endeavors===\nIn April 2016, SM Entertainment confirmed Mark alongside five other members of the SM Rookies program to debut as members of [[NCT (band)|NCT]] and its first subgroup, NCT U. On April 9, Mark, alongside [[Lee Tae-yong|Taeyong]], Doyoung, [[Ten (singer)|Ten]] and Jaehyun debuted with the digital single \"The 7th Sense\", which he and Taeyong participated in the writing of.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201604061758581112853_2|title=NCT U confirms lineup, set to unveil singles 'The 7th Sense,' 'Without You'|last=Son|first=Ji-hyoung|date=April 6, 2016|publisher=[[The Korea Herald]]|accessdate=April 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, SM confirmed Mark as a member of NCT's second subgroup, [[NCT 127]], alongside Taeyong, Taeil, Yuta, Jaehyun, Winwin and Haechan. NCT 127 made their official debut with ''[[NCT 127 (EP)|NCT #127]]'' and title track \"Fire Truck\" on July 10, 2016.<ref name=genre>{{cite web|url=http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201607101242101223011_1|title=NCT 127 \uc804\uace1 \uc74c\uc6d0 \uacf5\uac1c, \ubcf4\ub108\uc2a4\ud2b8\ub799\uae4c\uc9c0 \ucd1d 7\uace1 \uc218\ub85d|date=July 10, 2016|website=Herald Corporation|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, SM confirmed Mark as a member of NCT's third subgroup, [[NCT Dream]], alongside Renjun, Jeno, Haechan, Jaemin, Chenle and Jisung. The group made their official debut on August 24, 2016, with the single \"Chewing Gum\".\n\nIn September 2016, Mark featured on [[Henry Lau]]'s \"Going Through Your Heart\", an original soundtrack for the [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS]] drama, [[Sweet Stranger and Me]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/909461wpp/henry-ncts-mark-plus-kim-jong-kook-sing-ost-man-living-house|title= Henry And NCT\u2019s Mark Plus Kim Jong Kook To Sing OST For \"The Man Living In Our House\"|date=October 24, 2016|website=Soompi|language=en}}</ref> This marked his first solo endeavour since debuting under NCT. \n \nIn January 2017, Mark joined ''[[High School Rapper]]'', a survival hip hop reality TV show which aired on [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]].<ref name=\"crap-source1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/935159wpp/ncts-mark-audition-mnets-new-hip-hop-show-high-school-rapper|title= NCT\u2019s Mark To Audition For Mnet\u2019s New Hip Hop Show \"High School Rapper\"|date=January 9, 2017|website=Soompi|language=en}}</ref> He made it to the finals and performed an original song, \"Drop\" featuring labelmate, [[Kang Seul-gi|Seulgi]] of [[Red Velvet (group)|Red Velvet]]. He subsequently placed 7th overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/article/967909wpp/watch-high-school-rapper-reveals-final-winner-performances-special-guests|title= Watch: \"High School Rapper\" Reveals Final Winner And Performances With Special Guests|date=April 1, 2017|website=Soompi|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Mark collaborated with Exo's [[Xiumin]] on single, [[Young & Free]]. The single was released through [[SM Station Season 2|Season 2]] of SM Entertainment's digital music project [[SM Station]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/music/now/read?oid=311&aid=0000749346|title=\uc5d1\uc18c \uc2dc\uc6b0\ubbfc\u00b7NCT \ub9c8\ud06c, 'SM\uc2a4\ud14c\uc774\uc158'\uc73c\ub85c \uc2a4\ud398\uc15c \ub4c0\uc624 \uacb0\uc131|access-date=2017-06-29|language=ko}}</ref> In the same month, Mark appeared in the first season of the music variety show ''Snowball Project''. He teamed up with [[Park Jae-jung (singer)|Park Jae-jung]] and released \"Lemonade Love\" on July 21, also through SM Station, which was produced by former labelmate Henry Lau and [[Yoon Jong-shin]].<ref name=\"snowballproject\">{{cite web |title=\"\ub208\ub369\uc774 \ucd9c\uaca9\"...\ubc15\uc7ac\uc815X\ub9c8\ud06c, \u2018\ub808\ubaa8\ub124\uc774\ub4dc \ub7ec\ube0c\u2019 \uc624\ub298(21\uc77c) \ubc1c\ud45c |url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/014/0003847621 |website=n.news.naver.com |accessdate=June 30, 2019 |language=ko |date=July 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soompi.com/2017/05/23/sm-mystic-entertainment-team-new-music-variety-show/|title=Parc Jae Jung And NCT's Mark Are The First Team-Up For SM And Mystic Entertainment's New Variety Show {{!}} Soompi|website=www.soompi.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-07}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Mark was named as one of the main emcees of the music program ''[[Show! Music Core]]''. He subsequently left the program in January 2019 to focus on activities with NCT 127.<ref name=\"showmucic\">{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=213&aid=0001014733|title=\uc639\uc131\uc6b0\u00b7\ubbf8\ub098\u00b7\ub9c8\ud06c, '\uc74c\uc545\uc911\uc2ec' \u65b0 MC \ubc1c\ud0c1 [\uacf5\uc2dd]|date=January 26, 2018|website=Herald Corporation|language=ko}}</ref>\nIn May 2018, he became a regular cast member on the [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]] reality TV show ''[[It's Dangerous Beyond The Blankets]]''.<ref name=\"blankets\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=201805031602080410|title=MBC \uce21 \"NCT \ub9c8\ud06c \u2018\uc774\ubd88\ubc16\uc740 \uc704\ud5d8\ud574\u2019 \ucd9c\uc5f0 \ub17c\uc758\uc911\"|date=May 3, 2018}}</ref> In October 2018, Mark released the song \"Dream Me\" with Red Velvet's [[Joy (singer)|Joy]] for the soundtrack of the KBS drama ''[[The Ghost Detective]].''\n\nOn December 31, 2018, Mark became the first member to officially graduate from NCT Dream.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=109&aid=0003850884|title=\"[\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5] NCT \ub9c8\ud06c, \uc62c\ud574 \ub9c8\uc9c0\ub9c9\uc73c\ub85c NCT DREAM \uc878\uc5c5\u2026\uc878\uc5c5\uc1a1 \uc218\ub85d\"|date=August 26, 2018|accessdate=July 1, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nOn August 7, 2019, Mark was confirmed as a member of [[SuperM]], a \"K-pop supergroup\" created by SM Entertainment in collaboration with [[Capitol Records]]. The group's promotions began in October and were  focused at the American market.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Jeff Benjamin |title=Super M, 'The Avengers Of K-Pop,' Unveiled By SM Entertainment And Capitol Music Group |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffbenjamin/2019/08/07/super-m-the-avengers-of-k-pop-unveiled-by-sm-entertainment-and-capitol-music-group/#355dfa061381 |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=Forbes |date=7 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=SM Entertainment and Capitol Records Team Up to Launch Super M |url=https://www.billboard.com/video/bbnews080819tiffanykpop2-8526949 |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=Billboard |date=8 August 2019}}</ref> SuperM's [[SuperM (EP)|self-titled debut EP]] was released on October 4, 2019 with lead single \"Jopping\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/chart-beat/8532879/superm-the-1st-mini-album-billboard-200-no-1|title=SuperM Debuts at No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart With 'The 1st Mini Album'|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, it was announced by SM Entertainment that Mark would return to and take part in NCT Dream future activities, as the sub-unit was to be re-branded and shifted away from its previous age-based graduation system.<ref>https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/9357513/nct-dream-new-album-reload-return-of-mark</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|NCT discography|SuperM#Discography}}\n\n===Songs===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\" | Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! colspan=\